# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: qnx-rtos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Initially leading the emerging smartphone market in the late 2000s, the company struggled to gain a lasting presence against the iPhone and Android phones.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry led the smartphone market in many countries, particularly the United States until the announcement of the iPhone 4 in 2010, and in Indonesia throughout the early 2010s.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In 2010, BlackBerry was worth more than Adidas, MTV or Ben & Jerry's.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The company withered against the rapid rise of both Apple and Google.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] After the launch of BlackBerry 10, it transitioned to a cybersecurity enterprise software and services company under CEO John S.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In 2018, the last BlackBerry smartphone, the BlackBerry Key2 LE, was released.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In 2022, BlackBerry discontinued support for BlackBerry 10, ending their presence in the smartphone market.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry's software products are used by various businesses, car manufacturers, and government agencies to prevent hacking and ransomware attacks.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] They include BlackBerry Enterprise Server (BlackBerry Unified Endpoint Manager) and a Unified Endpoint Management (UEM) platform.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In 1995, RIM was financed by Canadian institutional and venture capital investors through a private placement in the privately held company.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Working Ventures Canadian Fund Inc. led the first venture round with a C$5,000,000 investment with the proceeds being used to complete the development of RIM's two-way paging system hardware and software.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] A total of C$30,000,000 in pre-IPO financing was raised by the company prior to its initial public offering on the Toronto Stock Exchange in January 1998 under the symbol RIM.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In 1996, RIM introduced the Interactive Pager, the first two-way messaging pager, and the RIM 900 OEM radio modem.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The company developed the pager prototype with the support of Intel Corporation.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The company worked with RAM Mobile Data and Ericsson to turn the Ericsson-developed Mobitex wireless data network into a two-way paging and wireless e-mail network.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Pivotal in this development was the release of the Inter@ctive Pager 950.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In August 1997, a prototype was presented to BellSouth executives, who were impressed with the device and agreed to a $70-million deal that involved the supply of 100,000 devices.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The pager started shipping in August 1998.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] About the size of a bar of soap, this device competed against the Skytel two-way paging network developed by Motorola.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In 1999, RIM introduced the BlackBerry 850 pager.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] This was also the first device to use the Blackberry OS.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Named after its keyboard's similarity to the druplets of the blackberry fruit, the device could receive push email from a Microsoft Exchange Server using its complementary server software, BlackBerry Enterprise Server (BES).
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Its introduction set the stage for the company's future enterprise-oriented products, such as the BlackBerry 957 in April 2000, the first BlackBerry smartphone.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The BlackBerry OS platform and BES continued to increase in functionality, while the incorporation of encryption and S/MIME support helped BlackBerry devices gain increased usage by governments and businesses.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] During fiscal 1999-2001, RIM's assets grew eight-fold due to massive capacity expansion.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] RIM soon began to introduce BlackBerry devices for the consumer market as well, beginning with the BlackBerry Pearl 8100—the first BlackBerry phone to include multimedia features such as a camera.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The Pearl series was highly successful, as was the subsequent Curve 8300 and Bold 9000 series.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Extensive carrier partnerships fueled the rapid expansion of BlackBerry users globally in both enterprise and consumer markets.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Despite the arrival of the first Apple iPhone in 2007, BlackBerry sustained market share growth well into 2011.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The introduction of Apple's iPhone on the AT&T network in the fall of 2007 in the United States prompted RIM to produce its first touchscreen smartphone for the competing network in 2008—the BlackBerry Storm.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] It sold well but suffered from mixed to poor reviews and poor customer satisfaction.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The iPhone initially lagged behind BlackBerry in both shipments and active users, due to RIM's head start and larger carrier distribution network.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In the United States, the BlackBerry user base peaked at approximately 21 million users in the fall of 2010.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] That quarter, the company's global subscriber base stood at 36 million users.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] As the iPhone and Google Android accelerated growth in the United States, the BlackBerry began to turn to other smartphone platforms.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Nonetheless, the BlackBerry line as a whole continued to enjoy success, spurred on by strong international growth.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] As of December 1, 2012, the company had 79 million BlackBerry users globally with only 9 million remaining in the United States.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Even as the company continued to grow worldwide, investors and media became increasingly alarmed about the company's ability to compete with devices from rival mobile operating systems iOS and Android.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] CNN cited BlackBerry as one of six endangered US-Canadian brands.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Analysts were also worried about the company's management structure.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Following numerous attempts to upgrade its existing Java platform, the company acquired QNX Software Systems to upgrade the BlackBerry platform, centered around its recently acquired real-time operating system QNX.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In March 2011, then-co-CEO Jim Balsillie suggested during a conference call that the "launch of some powerful new BlackBerrys" (eventually released as BlackBerry 10) would be in early 2012.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] However, analysts were "worried that promoting the mysterious, supposedly game-changing devices too early might hurt sales of existing BlackBerrys" (similar to the Osborne effect).
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The initial launch date was seen in retrospect as too ambitious and hurt the company's credibility at a time when its existing aging products steadily lost market share.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On September 27, 2010, RIM announced the BlackBerry PlayBook tablet, the first product running on the new QNX platform known as BlackBerry Tablet OS.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The BlackBerry PlayBook was officially released to U.S. and Canadian consumers on April 19, 2011.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] It was criticized for being rushed to market in an incomplete state, and sold poorly.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Following the shipments of 900,000 tablets during its first three quarters on market, slow sales and inventory pileups prompted the company to reduce prices and write down the inventory value by $485 million.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry's primary competitors were smartphones running Android OS, and the Apple iPhone.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] For a number of years, the BlackBerry was the leading smartphone in many markets, particularly the United States.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The arrival of the iPhone and later Google's Android platform caused a slowdown in BlackBerry growth and a decline in sales in some markets, most notably the United States, leading to negative media and analyst sentiment over the company's ability to continue independently.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] When Apple's iPhone was introduced in 2007, it generated substantial media attention, with numerous media outlets calling it a "BlackBerry killer".
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] While BlackBerry sales continued to grow, the newer iPhone grew at a faster rate.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The 87% drop in BlackBerry's stock price between 2010 and 2013 was primarily attributed to the performance of the iPhone handset.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The first three iPhone models generally lagged behind the BlackBerry in sales, as RIM had major advantages in carrier and enterprise support; however, Apple continued gaining market share.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In October 2008, Apple briefly passed RIM in quarterly sales when they announced they had sold 6.9 million iPhones to the 6.1 million sold by RIM, comparing partially overlapping quarters between the companies.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Though Apple's iPhone sales declined to 4.3 million in the subsequent quarter and RIM's increased to 7.8 million, for some investors this was a sign of weakness.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The iPhone began to sell more phones quarterly than the BlackBerry in 2010, brought on by the release of the iPhone 4.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In the United States, the BlackBerry hit its peak in September 2010, with almost 22 million users, or 37% of the 58.7 million American smartphones.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry then began to decline in use in the United States, with Apple's installed base in the United States finally passing it in April 2011.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Sales of the iPhone continued to accelerate, as did the smartphone market, while the BlackBerry began to lose users continuously in the United States.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] By February 2016, only 1.59 million (0.8%) of the 198.9 million smartphone users in the United States were running BlackBerry compared to 87.32 million (43.9%) on an iPhone.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Google's Android mobile operating system, running on hardware by a range of manufacturers including Sony, Motorola, HTC, Samsung, LG and many others ramped up the competition for BlackBerry.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In January 2010, barely 3 million (7.1%) of the 42.7 million Smartphones in use at the time in the United States were running Android, compared to 18 million BlackBerry devices (43%).
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Within a single year Android had passed the installed base of the BlackBerry in the United States.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] By February 2016, only 1.59 million (0.8%) of the 198.9 million smartphone users in the United States were running BlackBerry compared to 104.82 million (52.7%) running Android.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] While RIM's secure encrypted network was attractive to corporate customers, their handsets were sometimes considered less attractive to consumers than iPhone and Android smartphones.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Developers often developed consumer applications for those platforms and not the BlackBerry.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] During 2010s, even enterprise customers had begun to adopt BYOD policies due to employee feedback.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The company also faced criticism that its hardware and operating system were outdated and unappealing compared to the competition, as well as that the browsing capabilities were poorer.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Slowing growth prompted the company to undertake a lay-off of 2,000 employees in the summer of 2011.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In September 2011, the company's BlackBerry Internet Service suffered a massive outage, impacting millions of customers for several days.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The outage embarrassingly occurred as Apple prepared to launch the iPhone 4S, causing fears of mass defections from the platform.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Shortly afterwards, in October 2011, RIM unveiled BBX, a new platform for future BlackBerry smartphones that would be based on the same QNX-based platform as the PlayBook.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] However, due to an accusation of trademark infringement regarding the name BBX, the platform was renamed BlackBerry 10.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The task proved daunting, with the company delaying the launch in December 2011 to some time in 2012.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On January 22, 2012, Mike Lazaridis and Jim Balsillie resigned as the CEOs of the company, handing the reins over to executive Thorsten Heins.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On March 29, 2012, the company reported its first net loss in years.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Heins set about the task of restructuring the company, including announcing plans to lay off 5,000 employees, replacing numerous executives, and delaying BlackBerry 10 a second time into January 2013.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] After much criticism and numerous delays, RIM officially launched BlackBerry 10 and two new smartphones based on the platform, the BlackBerry Z10 and Q10, on January 30, 2013.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The BlackBerry Z10, the first BlackBerry smartphone running BlackBerry 10, debuted worldwide in January 2013, going on sale immediately in the U.K. with other countries following.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] A marked departure from previous BlackBerry phones, the Z10 featured a fully touch-based design, a dual-core processor, and a high-definition display.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry 10 had 70,000 applications available at launch, which the company expected would rise to 100,000 by the time the device made its debut in the United States.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In support of the launch, the company aired its first Super Bowl television advertisement in the U.S. and Canada during Super Bowl XLVII.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In discussing the decision to create a proprietary operating system instead of adopting an off-the-shelf platform such as Android, Heins noted, "If you look at other suppliers' ability to differentiate, there's very little wiggle room.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] We looked at it seriously—but if you understand what the promise of BlackBerry is to its user base it's all about getting stuff done.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Games, media, we have to be good at it but we have to support those guys who are ahead of the game.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Very little time to consume and enjoy content—if you stay true to that purpose you have to build on that basis.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] And if we want to serve that segment we can't do it on a me-too approach." Chief Operating Officer Kristian Tear remarked "We want to regain our position as the number one in the world", while Chief Marketing Officer Frank Boulben proclaimed "It could be the greatest comeback in tech history.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] They don't want a duopoly" (referring to Apple and Samsung).
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] During the BlackBerry 10 launch event, the company also announced that it would change its public brand from Research In Motion to BlackBerry.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The name change was made to "put the BlackBerry brand at the centre" of the company's diverse brands, and because customers in some markets "already know the company as BlackBerry".
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] A shareholder vote on an official name change to BlackBerry Limited was held at its next annual general meeting, after its ticker symbols on the TSX and NASDAQ already were changed to BB and BBRY respectively on February 4, 2013.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On August 12, 2013, the company announced that it was open to being purchased.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Canada Pension Plan Investment Board's CEO Mark Wiseman stated that he would consider investing in BlackBerry if the company became private.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Also on August 12, 2013, foremost shareholder Prem Watsa resigned from BlackBerry's board.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On September 20, 2013, the company announced it would lay off 4,500 staff and take a CAD$1 billion operating loss.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Three days later, the company announced that it had signed a letter of intent to be acquired by a consortium led by Prem Watsa-owned Fairfax Financial Holdings for a $9 per share deal.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On September 29, 2013, the company began operating a direct sales model for customers in the United States, where unlocked Q10 and Z10 smartphones were sold directly from the BlackBerry website.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On October 15, 2013, the company published an open letter in 30 publications in nine countries to reassure customers that BlackBerry would continue to operate.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On November 4, 2013, the Fairfax Prem Watsa deal was scrapped in favor of a US$1 billion cash injection which, according to one analyst, represented the level of confidence BlackBerry's largest shareholder had in the company.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] At the same time, BlackBerry installed John Chen as CEO to replace the laid-off Heins.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] According to the Globe and Mail, BlackBerry's hope was that Chen, with his reputation as a turnaround artist, could save the company.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] "We have begun moving the company to embrace a multi-platform, BYOD world by adopting a new mobility management platform and a new device strategy," Chen explained in an open letter published shortly after his appointment.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In April 2014, Chen spoke of his turnaround strategy in an interview with Reuters, explaining that he intended to invest in or partner with other companies in regulated industries such as healthcare, financial, and legal services.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In May 2014, the low-cost BlackBerry Z3 was introduced in the Indonesian market, where the brand had been particularly popular.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The budget handset was produced in partnership with Taiwanese manufacturer Foxconn Technology Group, which handled the design and distribution of the product.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In September 2015, Chen unveiled the BlackBerry Priv, a keyboard-slider smartphone utilizing the Android operating system with BlackBerry-developed software enhancements, including a secure bootloader, full-disk encryption, integrity protection, and the BlackBerry HUB.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In 2020, BlackBerry signed a new licensing agreement for smartphones with the US-based startup company, OnwardMobility.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The company never released a device before shutting down in 2022.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] As of June 2021, Cybersecurity ($107 million) and IoT ($43 million) revenue accounted for a combined 86% of Q1 2022 earnings ($174 million).
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On January 4, 2022, BlackBerry decommissioned the infrastructure and operating system used by their non-Android phones.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In October 2023, the company announced that it would spin off its IoT business unit and hold an initial public offering for it in the next year.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] During this time, BlackBerry also expanded its software and services offerings with several acquisitions.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] These included file security firm WatchDox, crisis communications leader AtHoc, and rival EMM vendor Good Technology.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The products offered by these firms were gradually re-branded and integrated into BlackBerry's own portfolio.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry also announced the release of the Good Secure EMM Suites, consolidating WatchDox and Good Technology's products into several tiered offerings alongside its existing software.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry announced the DTeK50, a mid-range Android smartphone, on July 26, 2016.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Unlike the Priv, the DTek50 was a re-branded version of an existing smartphone, the Alcatel Idol 4 as manufactured by TCL Corporation, one of the company's hardware partners.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The first of these partners was BB Merah Putih, a joint venture in Indonesia.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Chen stated that the company was "no longer just about the smartphone, but the smart in the phone".
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On December 15, 2016, BlackBerry announced that it had reached a long-term deal with TCL to continue producing BlackBerry-branded smartphones for sale outside of Bangladesh, India, Indonesia, Nepal, and Sri Lanka.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] This partnership was followed by an agreement with Optiemus Infracom on February 6, 2017, to produce devices throughout India and neighbouring markets including Sri Lanka, Nepal, and Bangladesh.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Since the partnerships were announced, TCL released the BlackBerry KeyOne and BB Merah Putih released the BlackBerry Aurora.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In February 2016, BlackBerry acquired UK-based cybersecurity firm Encription, with the intention of branching out into the security consulting business.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On December 8, 2016, BlackBerry announced the release of BlackBerry Secure.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Billed as a "comprehensive mobile security platform for the Enterprise of Things", BlackBerry Secure deepened the integration between BlackBerry's acquisitions and its core portfolio.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] According to Forbes, it brings all of BlackBerry's products "under a single umbrella".
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Also in February 2017, analyst firm 451 Research released a report on BlackBerry's improved financial position and product focus.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The report identified BlackBerry's position in the Internet of Things and its device licensing strategy as strengths.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Chen announced his resignation as CEO through an employee letter posted to the Blackberry Limited blog page stating he will cease his role on November 4, 2023.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Until 2013, the number of active BlackBerry users increased over time.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In the fourth quarter of fiscal year ended March 3, 2012, RIM shipped 11.1 million BlackBerry smartphones, down 21 percent from the previous quarter and it was the first decline in the quarter covering Christmas since 2006.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] For its fourth quarter, RIM announced a net loss of US$125 million (the last loss before this occurred in the fourth quarter of the fiscal year 2005).
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] RIM's loss of market share accelerated in 2011, due to the rapidly growing sales of Samsung and HTC Android handsets; RIM's annual market share in the U.S. dropped to just 3 percent, from 9 percent.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In the quarter ended June 28, 2012, RIM announced that the number of BlackBerry subscribers had reached 78 million globally.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Furthermore, RIM reported its first quarter revenue for the 2013 fiscal year, showing that the company incurred a GAAP net loss of US$518 million for the quarter, and announced a plan to implement a US$1 billion cost-saving initiative.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The company also announced the delay of the new BlackBerry 10 OS until the first quarter of 2013.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] After the release of the Apple iPhone 5 in September 2012, RIM CEO Thorsten Heins announced that the number of global users was up to 80 million, which sparked a 7% jump in shares.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On December 2, 2012, the company reported a decline in the global subscriber base of BlackBerry to 79 million, after peaking at an all-time high of 80 million the previous quarter.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Later that same month, media reports confirmed that BlackBerry lost US$1.049 billion during the second fiscal quarter of 2013.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Between 2010 and 2013, the stock price of the company dropped by 87 percent due to the widespread popularity of the iPhone.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Goldman Sachs estimated that, in June 2014, BlackBerry accounted for 1 percent share of smartphone sales, compared to a peak of around 20 percent in 2009.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] With the release of its financial results for the first fiscal quarter of 2015 in June 2014, Chen presented a more stable company that had incurred a lower amount of loss than previous quarters.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] *The New York Times* described "a smaller-than-expected quarterly loss." Following the news release, Chen stated that BlackBerry was comfortable with its position, and it is understood that his plan for the company mainly involves businesses and governments, rather than consumers.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The company was often criticized for its dual CEO structure.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Some saw this arrangement as a dysfunctional management structure and believed RIM acted as two companies, slowing the effort to release the new BlackBerry 10 operating system.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On June 30, 2011, an investor push for the company to split its dual-CEO structure was unexpectedly withdrawn after an agreement was made with RIM.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In 2007, co-CEO Jim Balsillie was forced to resign as chairman as the company announced a $250 million earnings restatement relating to mistakes in how it granted stock options.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Furthermore, an internal review found that hundreds of stock-option grants had been backdated, timed to a low share price to make them more lucrative.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In January 2009, Canadian regulators stated that they were seeking a record penalty of US$80 million from the top two executives, co-CEOs Jim Balsillie and Mike Lazaridis.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Furthermore, the Ontario Securities Commission (OSC) pushed for Balsillie to pay the bulk of any penalty and relinquish his seat on RIM's board of directors for a period of time.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On February 5, 2009, several executives and directors of Research In Motion agreed to pay the penalties to settle an investigation into the backdating of stock options.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The Ontario Securities Commission approved the arrangement in a closed-door meeting.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The three were also required to pay C$9-million to the OSC.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Balsillie resigned from RIM's board of directors temporarily and remained in his executive role.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In May 2010, almost immediately after the OSC sanctions expired, Balsillie was reappointed to the board in spite of strong shareholder objections.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Lazardis and Balsillie resigned as co-CEOs in January 2012.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] After years of tension, Balsillie left the company entirely, stepping down from his executive role in March 2012.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Following their resignations, they were replaced by a single CEO - former co-COO Thorsten Heins.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Heins hired investment banks RBC Capital Markets and JP Morgan to seek out potential buyers interested in RIM, while also redoubling efforts on releasing BlackBerry 10.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Following the assumption of role as CEO, Heins made substantial changes to the company's leadership team.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Changes included the departures of Chief Technology Officer David Yach; Chief Operating Officer Jim Rowan; Senior Vice President of Software Alan Brenner; Chief Legal Officer, Karima Bawa; and Chief Information Officer Robin Bienfait.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Following the leadership changes, Heins hired Kristian Tear to assume the role of Chief Operating Officer, Frank Boulben to fill the Chief Marketing Officer role and appointed Dan Dodge, the CEO of QNX, to take over as Chief Technology Officer.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Zipperstein was appointed as the new Vice President and Chief Legal Officer.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On March 28, 2013, Lazaridis relinquished his position as vice chairman and announced his resignation from the board of directors.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Later in the year, Heins was replaced by John S.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Chen, who assumed the CEO role in the first week of November.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Chen's compensation package mainly consists of BlackBerry shares—a total of 13 million—and he will be entitled to the entire number of shares after he has served the company for five years.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Heins received an exit package of $22 million.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Chen has a reputation as a "turnaround" CEO, turning the struggling enterprise software and services organization Sybase into enough of a success to sign a merger with SAP in 2010.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Chen was open about his plans for BlackBerry upon joining the company, announcing his intent to move away from hardware manufacturing to focus on enterprise software such as QNX, BlackBerry UEM, and AtHoc.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In June 2011, RIM announced its prediction that Q1 2011 revenue would drop for the first time in nine years, and also unveiled plans to reduce its workforce.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In July 2011, the company cut 2,000 jobs, the biggest lay-off in its history and the first major layoff since November 12, 2002, when the company laid off 10% of its workforce (200 employees).
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The lay-off reduced the workforce by around 11%, from 19,000 employees to 17,000.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On June 28, 2012, the company announced a planned workforce reduction of 5,000 by the end of its fiscal 2013, as part of a $1 billion cost savings initiative.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On July 25, 2013, 250 employees from BlackBerry's research and development department and new product testing were laid off.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The layoffs were part of the turnaround efforts.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On September 20, 2013, BlackBerry confirmed that the company will have a massive layoff of 4,500 employees by the end of 2013.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] This would be approximately 40 percent of the company's workforce.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry had at its peak about 20,000 employees.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] After CEO John Chen joined BlackBerry in 2013 there were additional layoffs in February 2015 to compete with smartphones, at which point the total employees numbered 6,225.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On July 21, 2015, BlackBerry announced an additional layoff of an unspecified number of employees, with another 200 laid off in February 2016.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] As of February 2022, the company had 3,225 employees.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The BlackBerry OS was intended to operate under much different, simpler conditions such as low powered devices, narrow network bandwidth, and high-security enterprises.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] However, the aging platform struggled with emerging trends like mobile web browsing, consumer applications, multimedia and touch screen interfaces.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Users experienced performance issues, usability problems and instability.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The company tried to enhance the old platform, but ultimately decided to build a new platform with QNX at its core.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The BlackBerry PlayBook was the first RIM product whose BlackBerry Tablet OS was built on QNX, launched in April 2011 as an alternative to the Apple iPad.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] However, it was criticized for having incomplete software and a poor app selection.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] It fared poorly until prices were substantially reduced, like most other tablet computers released that year.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The BlackBerry Tablet OS received a major update in February 2012, as well as numerous minor updates.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry 10, a substantially updated version of BlackBerry Tablet OS intended for the next generation BlackBerry smartphones, was originally planned for release in early 2012.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The company delayed the product several times, remembering the criticism faced by the BlackBerry Playbook launch and citing the need for it to be perfect in order to stand a chance in the market.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The most recent model with this OS was the BlackBerry Leap.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In September 2015, BlackBerry announced the Priv, a handset running Android 5.1.1 "Lollipop".
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] It is the first phone by the company not to run an in-house built operating system.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The version of Android running on the Priv is very similar to the standard version developed by Google, with some changes to improve productivity and security.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry implemented some of the features of BlackBerry 10 within Android, such as BlackBerry Hub, BlackBerry Virtual Keyboard, BlackBerry Calendar, and BlackBerry Contacts.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On July 26, 2016, a mid-range model with only an on-screen keyboard was introduced, the slim BlackBerry DTEK50, powered by the then-latest version of Android (6.0, Marshmallow) and featuring a 5.2-inch full high-definition display.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry chief security officer David Kleidermacher stressed data security during the launch, indicating that this model included built-in malware protection and encryption of all user information.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] By then, the BlackBerry Classic, which used the BlackBerry 10 OS, had been discontinued.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In July 2016, industry observers expected the company to announce two additional smartphones over the subsequent 12 months, presumably also with the Android OS.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In 2022, BlackBerry discontinued support for BlackBerry 10, effectively ending their presence in the smartphone market.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Through the years, particularly as the company moved towards cybersecurity, BlackBerry has made numerous acquisitions of third-party companies and technology.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Slipstream Data Inc was a network optimization/data compression/network acceleration software company.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry acquired the company as a wholly owned subsidiary on July 11, 2006.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The company continues to operate out of Waterloo.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The Certicom intellectual property portfolio includes over 350 patents and patents pending worldwide that cover key aspects of elliptic-curve cryptography (ECC).
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The National Security Agency (NSA) has licensed 26 of Certicom's ECC patents as a way of clearing the way for the implementation of elliptic curves to protect U.S. and allied government information.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On January 23, 2009, VeriSign entered into an agreement to acquire Certicom.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Research In Motion put in a counter-offer, which was deemed superior.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] VeriSign did not match this offer, and so Certicom announced an agreement to be acquired by RIM.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Upon the completion of this transaction, Certicom became a wholly owned subsidiary of RIM, and was de-listed from the Toronto Stock Exchange on March 25, 2009.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In June 2009, RIM announced they would acquire Dash Navigation, makers of the Dash Express.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The first product to contain this browser, the BlackBerry Torch 9800, was named after the company.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On September 8, 2010, **DataViz, Inc.** sold their office suite Documents To Go and other assets to Research In Motion for $50 million.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Subsequently, the application which allows users to view and edit Microsoft Word, Microsoft Excel and Microsoft PowerPoint was bundled on BlackBerry Smartphones and tablets.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On March 26, 2010, the company announced its acquisition of Viigo, a Toronto-based company that developed the popular Viigo for BlackBerry applications, which aggregated news content from around the web.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] RIM reached an agreement with Harman International on April 12, 2010, for RIM to acquire QNX Software Systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The acquired company was to serve as the foundation for the next generation BlackBerry platform that crossed devices.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] QNX became the platform for the BlackBerry PlayBook and BlackBerry 10 Smartphones.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In July 2011, RIM brought on JayCut, a Sweden-based company that is an online video editor.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] JayCut technology was incorporated into the media software of BlackBerry 10.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In March 2012, RIM acquired Paratek Microwave, bringing their adaptive RF Tuning technology into BlackBerry handsets.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On September 18, 2012, it was announced that the RIM social calendaring service, Tungle.me would be shut down on December 3, 2012.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In July 2011, RIM acquired NewBay, an Irish-based company that is an online video, pics and tool for media networks editor.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] RIM subsequently sold NewBay to Synchronoss in December 2012 for $55.5 million.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On June 7, 2011, Scoreloop was acquired by BlackBerry for US$71 million.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] It provided tools for adding social elements to any game (achievements/rewards etc.) and was central to the BlackBerry 10's Games app.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On December 1, 2014, all Scoreloop services were shut down.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Gist was acquired in February 2011, by BlackBerry.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Gist was a tool that helps users to organise and view all their contacts in one place.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Gist's services closed down on September 15, 2012, in order for the company to focus on BlackBerry 10.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry Ltd. acquired Scroon in May 2013.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The French startup manages Facebook, Twitter and other social-media accounts for large clients like luxury-good maker LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton SA, wireless operator Orange SA (ORA) and Warner Bros.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The deal was publicly announced in November 2013.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] According to Scroon founder, Alexandre Mars, he had not disclosed the purchase by BlackBerry before because of the "delicate media buzz" around the company.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Scroon is part of BlackBerry's strategy to profit from the BlackBerry Messenger instant-messaging service by utilizing the newly unveiled BBM Channels.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Movirtu was acquired in September 2014, by BlackBerry.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Movirtu is a U.K. startup that allows multiple phone numbers to be active on a single mobile device.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] At the time of the acquisition BlackBerry announced they would expand this functionality beyond BlackBerry 10 to other mobile platforms such as Android and iOS.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Secusmart was acquired in September 2014.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The German-based company was one of the steps to position BlackBerry as the most secure provider in the mobile market.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Secusmart had the agreement to equip the German Government with high secure mobile devices that encrypt voice as well as data on BlackBerry 10 devices.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Those phones are currently in use by Angela Merkel and most of the ministers as well as several Departments and the Parliament.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] WatchDox was an Israel-based Enterprise File Synchronization and Sharing company which specialized in securing access to documents on a cloud basis.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry acquired the company in April 2015.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On December 8, 2016, BlackBerry renamed WatchDox to BlackBerry Workspaces.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] In August 2019, BlackBerry closed down its Israel development center.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On July 22, 2015, BlackBerry announced that it had acquired AtHoc, a provider of secure, networked emergency communications.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On September 4, 2015, BlackBerry announced the acquisition of mobile security provider Good Technology for $425 million.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On December 8, 2016, it rebranded Good's products and integrated them into the BlackBerry Enterprise Mobility Suite, a set of tiered software offerings for its enterprise customers.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On February 24, 2016, BlackBerry acquired UK-based cyber security consultancy Encription.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On November 16, 2018, Cylance was purchased for US$1.4 billion by BlackBerry Limited in an all cash deal.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The technology behind Cylance would enable BlackBerry to add artificial intelligence capabilities to its existing software products for IoT applications and other services.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Cylance ran as a separate division within BlackBerry Limited's operations.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On December 16, 2024, it was announced that BlackBerry sold Cylance to Arctic Wolf for US$160 million.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] An Enterprise Mobility Management platform that provides provisional and access control over smartphones, tablets, laptops, and desktops with support for all major platforms including iOS, Android (including Android for Work and Samsung KNOX), BlackBerry 10, Windows 10, and Mac OS.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] UEM (formerly known as BES) also acts as a unified management console and server for BlackBerry Dynamics, BlackBerry Workspaces, and BlackBerry 2FA.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] A Mobile Application Management platform that manages and secures app data through application virtualization.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The BlackBerry Dynamics suite of apps includes email, calendar, contacts, tasks, instant messaging, browsing, and document sharing.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] The BlackBerry Dynamics SDK allows developers to utilize the platform's security, and add functionality from BlackBerry's other solutions into their applications.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] An Enterprise File Synchronization and Sharing (EFSS) platform, Workspaces provides file-level digital rights management controls alongside file synchronization and sharing functionality.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] A two-factor, certificate-based VPN authentication solution that allows users to authenticate without requiring PINs or passwords.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] An IP-based enterprise instant messaging platform that provides end-to-end encryption for voice, video, and text-based communication.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On February 7, 2017, Blackberry released the BBM Enterprise SDK, a "Communications Platform as a Service" kit that allows developers to incorporate BBM Enterprise's messaging capabilities into their own applications.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] Said capabilities include secure messaging, voice, video, file sharing, and presence information.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] An emergency communication system, AtHoc provides two-way messaging and notifications across a range of devices and platforms.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] On May 17, 2017, BlackBerry released AtHoc Account to help businesses more easily keep track of their staff in an emergency.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] An anti-eavesdropping solution that provides voice, data, and SMS encryption.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] A real-time embedded operating system, QNX drives multiple software systems in modern auto vehicles, and forms the basis of solutions like BlackBerry Radar, an IoT-based asset tracking system for the transportation industry.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p01] BlackBerry IVY is an edge-to-cloud vehicle data platform.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] Since the turn of the century, RIM has been embroiled in a series of suits relating to alleged patent infringement.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] In 2001, Research In Motion sued competitor Glenayre Electronics Inc. for patent infringement, partly in response to an earlier infringement suit filed by Glenayre against RIM.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] RIM sought an injunction to prevent Glenayre from infringing on RIM's "Single Mailbox Integration" patent.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] The suit was ultimately settled in favour of RIM.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] In June 2002, Research In Motion filed suit against 2000 start-up and competitor Good Technology.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] RIM filed additional complaints throughout the year.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] In March 2004, Good agreed to a licensing deal, thereby settling the outstanding litigation.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] On September 16, 2002, Research In Motion was awarded a patent pertaining to keyboard design on hand-held e-mail devices.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] Upon receiving the patent, it proceeded to sue Handspring over its Treo device.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] Handspring eventually agreed to license RIM's patent and avoid further litigation in November of the same year.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] During the appeals, RIM discovered new prior art that raised a "substantial new question of patentability" and filed for a reexamination of the NTP patents in the United States Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] That reexamination was conducted separately to the court cases for infringement.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] In February 2006, the USPTO rejected all of NTP's claims in three disputed patents.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] NTP appealed the decision, and the reexamination process was still ongoing as of July 2006 (See NTP, Inc. for details).
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] On March 3, 2006, RIM announced that it had settled its BlackBerry patent dispute with NTP.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] Under the terms of the settlement, RIM agreed to pay NTP US$612.5 million in a "full and final settlement of all claims".
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] In a statement, RIM said that "all terms of the agreement have been finalized and the litigation against RIM has been dismissed by a court order this afternoon.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] On July 17, 2003, while still embroiled in litigation with NTP and Good Technology, RIM filed suit against Xerox in the U.S.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] The suit was filed in response to discussions about patents held by Xerox that might affect RIM's business and also asked that patents held by Xerox be invalidated.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] On May 1, 2006, RIM was sued by Visto for infringement of four patents.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] Though the patents were widely considered invalid and in the same veins as the NTP patents – with a judgement going against Visto in the U.K. – RIM settled the lawsuit in the United States on July 16, 2009, with RIM agreeing to pay Visto US$267.5 million plus other undisclosed terms.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] On January 22, 2010, Motorola requested that all BlackBerry smartphones be banned from being imported into the United States for infringing upon five of Motorola's patents.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] Their patents for "early-stage innovations", including UI, power management and WiFi, are in question.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] RIM countersued later the same day, alleging anti-competitive behaviour and that Motorola had broken a 2003 licensing agreement by refusing to extend licensing terms beyond 2008.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] The companies settled out of court on June 11, 2010.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] On December 5, 2011, Research In Motion obtained an order granting its motion to dismiss plaintiff Eatoni's claims that RIM violated Section 2 of the Sherman Antitrust Act and equivalent portions of New York's Donnelly Act.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] Eatoni alleged that RIM's alleged infringement of plaintiff's '317 patent constituted an antitrust violation.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] In July 2012, a U.S. federal court jury awarded damages (later overturned) of $147 million against Research In Motion.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] The jury decided that Research In Motion had violated patents of Mformation and calculated damages of $8 each on 18.4 million units for royalties on past sales of devices to nongovernment U.S. customers only, not including future royalty payments inside and outside the U.S.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] On August 9, 2012, that verdict was overturned on appeal.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] RIM had argued that Mformation's patent claims were invalid because the processes were already being used when Mformation filed its patent application.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] Judge James Ware said Mformation failed to establish that RIM had infringed on the company's patent.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] On May 26, 2017, BlackBerry announced that it had reached an agreement with Qualcomm Incorporated resolving all amounts payable in connection with the interim arbitration decision announced on April 12, 2017.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] On March 8, 2018, BlackBerry Limited sued Facebook Inc. in federal court in Los Angeles.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] According to BlackBerry Limited, Facebook has built swaths of its empire on the messaging technology which was originally developed by them during the time when the Facebook chief, Mark Zuckerberg, was still living in a Harvard University dorm room.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] Blackberry Limited alleged that many features of the Facebook messaging service infringe on BlackBerry patents.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] In January 2021, BlackBerry shares jumped 20% after settling its patent dispute with Facebook.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] In November 2011, Blackberry, then RIM, was ranked 15th out of 15 electronics manufacturers in Greenpeace's re-launched Guide to Greener Electronics.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] In its 2012 report on progress relating to conflict minerals, the Enough Project rated RIM the sixth highest of 24 consumer electronics companies.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] In 2014, RIM partnered with Solutions for Hope to expand the number of conflict-free mineral regions in the Congo.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] On October 10, 2011, RIM experienced one of the worst service outages in the company's history.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] Tens of millions of BlackBerry users in Europe, the Middle East, Africa, and North America were unable to receive or send emails and BBM messages through their phones.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] After a four-year stand-off with the Indian government over access to RIM's secure networks, the company demonstrated the ability to intercept consumer email and messaging traffic between BlackBerry handsets, and make these encrypted communications available to Indian security agencies.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] This agreement does not include its enterprise services.
[src:qnx-rtos/blackberry-limited-p02] Through the Canadian Mutual Legal Assistance in Criminal Matters Act, Blackberry has given its master encryption keys to law enforcement, allowing the Royal Canadian Mounted Police to view communications and other encrypted information.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] Driven by the demand for more connected vehicles, in-car entertainment is getting more and more sophisticated.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] Car makers, electronics and software suppliers, as well as newcomers from the Silicon Valley (such as Google and Apple), work together and also compete to come up with infotainment systems that are user-friendly and safe to use.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] ICE systems are increasingly commonplace with newer vehicle models and several auto makers have developed their own systems: Ford with SYNC and MyFord Touch, Toyota with Entune, Cadillac with CUE (Cadillac User Experience), FCA with Uconnect, etc.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] With the mass adoption of smartphones worldwide, a new issue has emerged: the use of connected devices in the car.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] According to a 2015 survey conducted by AT&T with a sample of over 2,000 US respondents, "7-in-10 people engage in smartphone activities while driving" including social media (40%), web browsing (30%) and even video chatting (10%).
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] This raises safety concerns related to distracted driving and also pushes the automotive industry to integrate those devices in a safe manner.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] "Traditional" car makers increasingly rely on the software and electronics expertise of auto suppliers and technology companies to help them design such systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] Policies regarding in-car entertainment systems are less developed than cell phone usage laws regarding similar distractions in cars.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] Domestic rules for Telecom-, data protection and lawful access can be applicable, but the legal environment is diverse and different for each country.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] In the United States, 10 states, D.C., Guam, and the Virgin Islands prohibit all drivers from using handheld cell phones while driving.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] Additionally, 39 states, D.C., Guam, and the Virgin Islands ban text messaging for all drivers.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] However, few states have developed laws to limit the content that drivers can view on in-car entertainment systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] Still, researchers are beginning to analyze the potential impact of distracted drivers on the roads.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] Charlie Klauer, a researcher at the Virginia Tech Transportation Institute, says that drivers who look at screens have a much higher risk of crashing.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] Furthermore, the risk of crashing rises exponentially the longer a driver has taken their eyes off the road.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] Automotive companies like Ford and Audi contend that they have tested and revised their latest systems in order to reduce the amount of time that drivers spend looking away from the road.
[src:qnx-rtos/in-vehicle-infotainment] As car infotainment systems can access more and more functions of the vehicle (e.g. through the CAN bus), concerns have also been voiced about potential remote car hacking (see drive by wire).
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] In computer science, **message passing** is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message to a process (which may be an actor or object) and relies on that process and its supporting infrastructure to then select and run some appropriate code.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Message passing differs from conventional programming where a process, subroutine, or function is directly invoked by name.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Message passing is key to some models of concurrency and object-oriented programming.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Message passing is ubiquitous in modern computer software.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] It is used as a way for the objects that make up a program to work with each other and as a means for objects and systems running on different computers (e.g., the Internet) to interact.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Message passing may be implemented by various mechanisms, including channels.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Message passing is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] In contrast to the traditional technique of calling a program by name, message passing uses an object model to distinguish the general function from the specific implementations.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message and relies on the object to select and execute the appropriate code.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] The justifications for using an intermediate layer essentially falls into two categories: encapsulation and distribution.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Message passing is a core technique used for communication between processes, threads, objects, or nodes in both concurrent and distributed systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] It enables software components to exchange information without sharing memory, often using communication channels, buffers, or middleware to transport messages between senders and receivers.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] In some models, message passing can be implemented synchronously, where the sender waits for a reply, or asynchronously, where messages are queued for later processing.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Encapsulation is the idea that software objects should be able to invoke services on other objects without knowing or caring about how those services are implemented.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Encapsulation can reduce the amount of coding logic and make systems more maintainable.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] E.g., rather than having IF-THEN statements that determine which subroutine or function to call, a developer can just send a message to the object and the object will select the appropriate code based on its type.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] One of the first examples of how this can be used was in the domain of computer graphics.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] There are various complexities involved in manipulating graphic objects.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] For example, simply using the right formula to compute the area of an enclosed shape will vary depending on if the shape is a triangle, rectangle, ellipse, or circle.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] In traditional computer programming, this would result in long IF-THEN statements testing what sort of object the shape was and calling the appropriate code.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] The object-oriented way to handle this is to define a class called `Shape` with subclasses such as `Rectangle` and `Ellipse` (which, in turn, have subclasses `Square` and `Circle`) and then to simply send a message to any `Shape` asking it to compute its area.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Each `Shape` object will then invoke the subclass's method with the formula appropriate for that kind of object.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Distributed message passing provides developers with a layer of the architecture that provides common services to build systems made up of sub-systems that run on disparate computers in different locations and at different times.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Synchronous message passing occurs between objects that are running at the same time.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] It is used by object-oriented programming languages such as Java and Smalltalk.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Synchronous messaging is analogous to a synchronous function call; just as the function caller waits until the function completes, the sending process waits until the receiving process accepts the message.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] This can make synchronous communication unworkable for some applications.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] For example, large, distributed systems may not perform well enough to be usable.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Such large, distributed systems may need to operate while some of their subsystems are down for maintenance, etc.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Imagine a busy business office having 100 desktop computers that send emails to each other using synchronous message passing exclusively.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] One worker turning off their computer can cause the other 99 computers to freeze until the worker turns their computer back on to process a single email.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Message passing systems can be broadly categorized based on how send and receive operations interact with executing processes.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] In **synchronous** message passing, the sending process may block until the receiver has accepted the message, ensuring tight coordination.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] In **asynchronous** models, the sender continues execution after sending a message, and messages are typically stored in a queue or buffer until the receiving process retrieves them.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] With asynchronous message passing the receiving object can be down or busy when the requesting object sends the message.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Continuing the function call analogy, it is like a function call that returns immediately, without waiting for the called function to complete.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Messages are sent to a queue where they are stored until the receiving process requests them.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] The receiving process processes its messages and sends results to a queue for pickup by the original process (or some designated next process).
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Asynchronous messaging requires additional capabilities for storing and retransmitting data for systems that may not run concurrently, and are generally handled by an intermediary level of software (often called middleware); a common type being Message-oriented middleware (MOM).
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] The buffer required in asynchronous communication can cause problems when it is full.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] A decision has to be made whether to block the sender or whether to discard future messages.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] If messages are dropped, communication is no longer reliable.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Synchronous communication can be built on top of asynchronous communication by using a Synchronizer.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] For example, the α-Synchronizer works by ensuring that the sender always waits for an acknowledgement message from the receiver.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] The sender only sends the next message after the acknowledgement has been received.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] On the other hand, asynchronous communication can also be built on top of synchronous communication.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] For example, modern microkernels generally only provide a synchronous messaging primitive and asynchronous messaging can be implemented on top by using helper threads.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Message-passing systems use either distributed or local objects.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] With distributed objects the sender and receiver may be on different computers, running different operating systems, using different programming languages, etc.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] In this case the bus layer takes care of details about converting data from one system to another, sending and receiving data across the network, etc.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] The Remote Procedure Call (RPC) protocol in Unix was an early example of this.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] With this type of message passing it is not a requirement that sender nor receiver use object-oriented programming.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Procedural language systems can be wrapped and treated as large grained objects capable of sending and receiving messages.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Examples of systems that support distributed objects are: Emerald, ONC RPC, CORBA, Java RMI, DCOM, SOAP, .NET Remoting, CTOS, QNX Neutrino RTOS, OpenBinder and D-Bus.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Distributed object systems have been called "shared nothing" systems because the message passing abstraction hides underlying state changes that may be used in the implementation of sending messages.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Distributed, or asynchronous, message-passing has additional overhead compared to calling a procedure.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] In message-passing, arguments must be copied to the new message.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Some arguments can contain megabytes of data, all of which must be copied and transmitted to the receiving object.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Traditional procedure calls differ from message-passing in terms of memory usage, transfer time and locality.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Arguments are passed to the receiver typically by general-purpose registers requiring no additional storage nor transfer time, or in a parameter list containing the arguments' addresses (a few bits).
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Address-passing is not possible for distributed systems since the systems use separate address spaces.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Web browsers and web servers are examples of processes that communicate by message-passing.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] A URL is an example of referencing a resource without exposing process internals.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] A subroutine call or method invocation will not exit until the invoked computation has terminated.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Asynchronous message-passing, by contrast, can result in a response arriving a significant time after the request message was sent.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] A message-handler will, in general, process messages from more than one sender.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] This means its state can change for reasons unrelated to the behavior of a single sender or client process.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] This is in contrast to the typical behavior of an object upon which methods are being invoked: the latter is expected to remain in the same state between method invocations.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] In other words, the message-handler behaves analogously to a volatile object.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] The prominent mathematical models of message passing are the Actor model and Pi calculus.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] In mathematical terms a message is the single means to pass control to an object.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] If the object responds to the message, it has a method for that message.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] Alan Kay has argued that message passing is more important than objects in OOP, and that objects themselves are often over-emphasized.
[src:qnx-rtos/message-passing] The live distributed objects programming model builds upon this observation; it uses the concept of a distributed data flow to characterize the behavior of a complex distributed system in terms of message patterns, using high-level, functional-style specifications.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In computer science, a **microkernel** (often abbreviated as **μ-kernel**) is the near-minimum amount of software that can provide the mechanisms needed to implement an operating system (OS).
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] These mechanisms include low-level address space management, thread management, and inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] If the hardware provides multiple rings or CPU modes, the microkernel may be the only software executing at the most privileged level, which is generally referred to as supervisor or kernel mode.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Traditional operating system functions, such as device drivers, protocol stacks and file systems, are typically removed from the microkernel and are instead run in user space.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Microkernels often have less source code than monolithic kernels.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The MINIX 3 microkernel, for example, has only approximately 12,000 lines of code.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Microkernels trace their roots back to Danish computer pioneer Per Brinch Hansen and his tenure in Danish computer company Regnecentralen, where he led software development efforts for the RC 4000 computer.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In 1967, Regnecentralen was installing a RC 4000 prototype in the Zakłady Azotowe Puławy fertilizer plant in Poland.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The computer used a small real-time operating system tailored for the needs of the plant.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Brinch Hansen and his team became concerned with the lack of generality and reusability of the RC 4000 system.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] They feared that each installation would require a different operating system, so they investigated novel and more general ways of creating software for the RC 4000.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In 1969, their effort resulted in the completion of the RC 4000 Multiprogramming System.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Its nucleus provided inter-process communication based on message-passing for up to 23 unprivileged processes, out of which 8 at a time were protected from one another.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] It further implemented scheduling of time slices of programs executed in parallel, initiation and control of program execution at the request of other running programs, and initiation of data transfers to or from peripherals.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Besides these elementary mechanisms, it had no built-in strategy for program execution and resource allocation.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This strategy was to be implemented by a hierarchy of running programs in which parent processes had complete control over child processes and acted as their operating systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Following Brinch Hansen's work, microkernels have been developed since the 1970s.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The term microkernel itself first appeared no later than 1981.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Microkernels were meant as a response to changes in the computer world, and to several challenges adapting existing "mono-kernels" to these new systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] New device drivers, protocol stacks, file systems and other low-level systems were being developed all the time.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This code was normally located in the monolithic kernel, and thus required considerable work and careful code management to work on.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Microkernels were developed with the idea that all of these services would be implemented as user-space programs, like any other, allowing them to be worked on monolithically and started and stopped like any other program.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This would not only allow these services to be more easily worked on, but also separated the kernel code to allow it to be finely tuned without worrying about unintended side effects.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Moreover, it would allow entirely new operating systems to be "built up" on a common core, aiding OS research.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Microkernels were a hot topic in the 1980s when the first usable local area networks were being introduced.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The AmigaOS Exec kernel was an early example, introduced in 1986 and used in a PC with relative commercial success.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The lack of memory protection, considered in other respects a flaw, allowed this kernel to have high message-passing performance because it did not need to copy data while exchanging messages between user-space programs.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The same mechanisms that allowed the kernel to be distributed into user space also allowed the system to be distributed across network links.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The first microkernels, notably Mach, created by Richard Rashid, proved to have disappointing performance, but the inherent advantages appeared so great that it was a major line of research into the late 1990s.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] However, during this time the speed of computers grew greatly in relation to networking systems, and the disadvantages in performance came to overwhelm the advantages in development terms.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Many attempts were made to adapt the existing systems to have better performance, but the overhead was always considerable and most of these efforts required the user-space programs to be moved back into the kernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] By 2000, most large-scale Mach kernel efforts had ended, although Apple's macOS, released in 2001, still uses a hybrid kernel called XNU, which combines a heavily modified (hybrid) OSF/1's Mach kernel (OSF MK 7.3 kernel) with code from BSD UNIX; this kernel is also used in iOS, tvOS, and watchOS.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Windows NT, starting with NT 3.1 and continuing with Windows 11, uses a hybrid kernel design.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] As of 2012, the Mach-based GNU Hurd is also functional and included in testing versions of Arch Linux and Debian.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Although major work on microkernels had largely ended, experimenters continued development.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Using a more pragmatic approach to the problem, including assembly code and relying on the processor to enforce concepts normally supported in software led to a new series of microkernels with dramatically improved performance.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Microkernels are closely related to exokernels.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] They also have much in common with hypervisors, but the latter make no claim to minimality and are specialized to supporting virtual machines; the L4 microkernel frequently finds use in a hypervisor capacity.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Early operating system kernels were rather small, partly because computer memory was limited.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] As the capability of computers grew, the number of devices the kernel had to control also grew.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Throughout the early history of Unix, kernels were generally small, even though they contained various device drivers and file system implementations.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] When address spaces increased from 16 to 32 bits, kernel design was no longer constrained by the hardware architecture, and kernels grew larger.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD) of Unix began the era of larger kernels.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In addition to operating a basic system consisting of the CPU, disks and printers, BSD added a complete TCP/IP networking system and a number of "virtual" devices that allowed the existing programs to work "invisibly" over the network.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This growth continued for many years, resulting in kernels with millions of lines of source code.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] As a result of this growth, kernels were prone to bugs and became increasingly difficult to maintain.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The microkernel was intended to address this growth of kernels and the difficulties that resulted.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In theory, the microkernel design allows for easier management of code due to its division into user space services.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This also allows for increased security and stability resulting from the reduced amount of code running in kernel mode.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] For example, if a networking service crashed due to buffer overflow, only the networking service's memory would be corrupted, leaving the rest of the system still functional.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Inter-process communication (IPC) is any mechanism which allows separate processes to communicate with each other, usually by sending messages.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Shared memory is, strictly defined, also an inter-process communication mechanism, but the abbreviation IPC usually refers to message passing only, and it is the latter that is particularly relevant to microkernels.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] IPC allows the operating system to be built from a number of smaller programs called servers, which are used by other programs on the system, invoked via IPC.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Most or all support for peripheral hardware is handled in this fashion, with servers for device drivers, network protocol stacks, file systems, graphics, etc.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Asynchronous IPC is analogous to network communication: the sender dispatches a message and continues executing.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The receiver checks (polls) for the availability of the message, or is alerted to it via some notification mechanism.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Asynchronous IPC requires that the kernel maintains buffers and queues for messages, and deals with buffer overflows; it also requires double copying of messages (sender to kernel and kernel to receiver).
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In synchronous IPC, the first party (sender or receiver) blocks until the other party is ready to perform the IPC.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] It does not require buffering or multiple copies, but the implicit rendezvous can make programming tricky.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Most programmers prefer asynchronous send and synchronous receive.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] First-generation microkernels typically supported synchronous as well as asynchronous IPC, and suffered from poor IPC performance.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Jochen Liedtke assumed the design and implementation of the IPC mechanisms to be the underlying reason for this poor performance.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In his L4 microkernel he pioneered methods that lowered IPC costs by an order of magnitude.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] These include an IPC system call that supports a send as well as a receive operation, making all IPC synchronous, and passing as much data as possible in registers.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Furthermore, Liedtke introduced the concept of the *direct process switch*, where during an IPC execution an (incomplete) context switch is performed from the sender directly to the receiver.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] If, as in L4, part or all of the message is passed in registers, this transfers the in-register part of the message without any copying at all.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Furthermore, the overhead of invoking the scheduler is avoided; this is especially beneficial in the common case where IPC is used in a remote procedure call (RPC) type fashion by a client invoking a server.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Another optimization, called *lazy scheduling*, avoids traversing scheduling queues during IPC by leaving threads that block during IPC in the ready queue.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Once the scheduler is invoked, it moves such threads to the appropriate waiting queue.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] As in many cases a thread gets unblocked before the next scheduler invocation, this approach saves significant work.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Similar approaches have since been adopted by QNX and MINIX 3.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In a series of experiments, Chen and Bershad compared memory cycles per instruction (MCPI) of monolithic Ultrix with those of microkernel Mach combined with a 4.3BSD Unix server running in user space.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Their results explained Mach's poorer performance by higher MCPI and demonstrated that IPC alone is not responsible for much of the system overhead, suggesting that optimizations focused exclusively on IPC will have a limited effect.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Liedtke later refined Chen and Bershad's results by making an observation that the bulk of the difference between Ultrix and Mach MCPI was caused by capacity cache-misses and concluding that drastically reducing the cache working set of a microkernel will solve the problem.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In a client-server system, most communication is essentially synchronous, even if using asynchronous primitives, as the typical operation is a client invoking a server and then waiting for a reply.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] As it also lends itself to more efficient implementation, most microkernels generally followed L4's lead and only provided a synchronous IPC primitive.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Asynchronous IPC could be implemented on top by using helper threads.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] However, experience has shown that the utility of synchronous IPC is dubious: synchronous IPC forces a multi-threaded design onto otherwise simple systems, with the resulting synchronization complexities.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Moreover, an RPC-like server invocation sequentializes client and server, which should be avoided if they are running on separate cores.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Versions of L4 deployed in commercial products have therefore found it necessary to add an asynchronous notification mechanism to better support asynchronous communication.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This signal-like mechanism does not carry data and therefore does not require buffering by the kernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] By having two forms of IPC, they have nonetheless violated the principle of minimality.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Other versions of L4 have switched to asynchronous IPC completely.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] As synchronous IPC blocks the first party until the other is ready, unrestricted use could easily lead to deadlocks.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Furthermore, a client could easily mount a denial-of-service attack on a server by sending a request and never attempting to receive the reply.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Therefore, synchronous IPC must provide a means to prevent indefinite blocking.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Many microkernels provide timeouts on IPC calls, which limit the blocking time.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In practice, choosing sensible timeout values is difficult, and systems almost inevitably use infinite timeouts for clients and zero timeouts for servers.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] As a consequence, the trend is towards not providing arbitrary timeouts, but only a flag which indicates that the IPC should fail immediately if the partner is not ready.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This approach effectively provides a choice of the two timeout values of zero and infinity.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Recent versions of L4 and MINIX have gone down this path (older versions of L4 used timeouts).
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] QNX avoids the problem by requiring the client to specify the reply buffer as part of the message send call.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] When the server replies the kernel copies the data to the client's buffer, without having to wait for the client to receive the response explicitly.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Microkernel servers are essentially daemon programs like any others, except that the kernel grants some of them privileges to interact with parts of physical memory that are otherwise off limits to most programs.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This allows some servers, particularly device drivers, to interact directly with hardware.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] A basic set of servers for a general-purpose microkernel includes file system servers, device driver servers, networking servers, display servers, and user interface device servers.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This set of servers (drawn from QNX) provides roughly the set of services offered by a Unix monolithic kernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The necessary servers are started at system startup and provide services, such as file, network, and device access, to ordinary application programs.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] With such servers running in the environment of a user application, server development is similar to ordinary application development, rather than the build-and-boot process needed for kernel development.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Additionally, many "crashes" can be corrected by simply stopping and restarting the server, which would not be feasible if the entire kernel had to reboot.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] However, part of the system state is lost with the failing server, hence this approach requires applications to cope with failure.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] A good example is a server responsible for TCP/IP connections: If this server is restarted, applications will experience a "lost" connection, a normal occurrence in a networked system.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] For other services, failure is less expected and may require changes to application code.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] For QNX, restart capability is offered as the QNX High Availability Toolkit.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Device drivers frequently perform direct memory access (DMA), and therefore can write to arbitrary locations of physical memory, including various kernel data structures.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] It is a common misconception that this means that they must be part of the kernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In fact, a driver is not inherently more or less trustworthy by being part of the kernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Furthermore, many devices are not DMA-capable; their drivers can be made untrusted by running them in user space.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Recently, an increasing number of computers feature IOMMUs, many of which can be used to restrict a device's access to physical memory.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This also allows user-mode drivers to become untrusted.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] User-mode drivers actually predate microkernels.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The Michigan Terminal System (MTS), in 1967, supported user-space drivers (including its file-system support), the first operating system to be designed with that capability.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Historically, drivers were less of a problem, as the number of devices was small and trusted anyway, so having them in the kernel simplified the design and avoided potential performance problems.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This led to the traditional driver-in-the-kernel style of Unix, Linux, and Windows NT.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] With the proliferation of various kinds of peripherals, the amount of driver code escalated and in modern operating systems dominates the kernel in code size.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] As a microkernel must allow building arbitrary operating system services on top, it must provide some core functionality.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This minimal design was pioneered by Brinch Hansen's Nucleus and the hypervisor of IBM's VM.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Everything else can be done in a user-mode program, although device drivers implemented as user programs may on some processor architectures require special privileges to access I/O hardware.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Related to the minimality principle, and equally important for microkernel design, is the separation of mechanism and policy, which enables the construction of arbitrary systems on top of a minimal kernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Any policy built into the kernel cannot be overwritten at user level and therefore limits the generality of the microkernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Policy implemented in user-level servers can be changed by replacing the servers (or letting the application choose between competing servers offering similar services).
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] For efficiency, most microkernels contain schedulers and manage timers, in violation of the minimality principle and the principle of policy-mechanism separation.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Startup (booting) of a microkernel-based system requires device drivers, which are not part of the kernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Typically, this means that they are packaged with the kernel in the boot image, and the kernel supports a bootstrap protocol that defines how the drivers are located and started; this is the traditional bootstrap procedure of L4 microkernels.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Some microkernels, such as LynxOS and the original Minix, simplify this by placing some key drivers inside the kernel (in violation of the minimality principle).
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Some even include a file system in the kernel to simplify booting.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] A microkernel-based system may boot via multiboot compatible boot loader.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Such systems usually load statically linked servers to make an initial bootstrap or mount an OS image to continue bootstrapping.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] A key component of a microkernel is a good IPC system and virtual-memory-manager design that allows implementing page-fault handling and swapping in user-mode servers in a safe way.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Since all services are performed by user-mode programs, efficient means of communication between programs are essential, far more so than in monolithic kernels.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The design of the IPC system makes or breaks a microkernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] To be effective, the IPC system must not only have low overhead, but also interact well with CPU scheduling.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] On most mainstream processors, obtaining a service is inherently more expensive in a microkernel-based system than a monolithic system.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In the monolithic system, the service is obtained by a single system call, which requires two *mode switches* (changes of the processor's ring or CPU mode).
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In the microkernel-based system, the service is obtained by sending an IPC message to a server, and obtaining the result in another IPC message from the server.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This requires a context switch if the drivers are implemented as processes, or a function call if they are implemented as procedures.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In addition, passing actual data to the server and back may incur extra copying overhead, while in a monolithic system the kernel can directly access the data in the client's buffers.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Performance is therefore a potential issue in microkernel systems, and first-generation microkernels such as Mach and ChorusOS indeed performed poorly.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] However, Jochen Liedtke showed that Mach's performance problems were the result of poor design and implementation, specifically Mach's excessive cache footprint.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Liedtke demonstrated with his own L4 microkernel that through careful design and implementation, and especially by following the minimality principle, IPC costs could be reduced by more than an order of magnitude compared to Mach.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] L4's IPC performance is still unbeaten across a range of architectures.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] While these results demonstrate that the poor performance of systems based on first-generation microkernels is not representative for second-generation kernels such as L4, this constitutes no proof that microkernel-based systems can be built with good performance.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] It has been shown that a monolithic Linux server ported to L4 exhibits only a few percent overhead over native Linux.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] However, such a single-server system exhibits few, if any, of the advantages microkernels are supposed to provide by structuring operating system functionality into separate servers.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] A number of commercial multi-server systems exist, in particular the real-time systems QNX and Integrity.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] No comprehensive comparison of performance relative to monolithic systems has been published for those multiserver systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Furthermore, performance does not seem to be the overriding concern for those commercial systems, which instead emphasize reliably quick interrupt handling response times (QNX) and simplicity for the sake of robustness.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] An attempt to build a high-performance multiserver operating system was the IBM Sawmill Linux project.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] However, this project was never completed.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] It has been shown in the meantime that user-level device drivers can come close to the performance of in-kernel drivers even for such high-throughput, high-interrupt devices as Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This seems to imply that high-performance multi-server systems are possible.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The security benefits of microkernels have been frequently discussed.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In the context of security the minimality principle of microkernels is, some have argued, a direct consequence of the principle of least privilege, according to which all code should have only the privileges needed to provide required functionality.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Minimality requires that a system's trusted computing base (TCB) should be kept minimal.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] As the kernel (the code that executes in the privileged mode of the hardware) has unvetted access to any data and can thus violate its integrity or confidentiality, the kernel is always part of the TCB.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Minimizing it is natural in a security-driven design.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Consequently, microkernel designs have been used for systems designed for high-security applications, including KeyKOS, EROS and military systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In fact common criteria (CC) at the highest assurance level (Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) 7) has an explicit requirement that the target of evaluation be "simple", an acknowledgment of the practical impossibility of establishing true trustworthiness for a complex system.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Again, the term "simple" is misleading and ill-defined.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In 2018, a paper presented at the Asia-Pacific Systems Conference claimed that microkernels were demonstrably safer than monolithic kernels by investigating all published critical CVEs for the Linux kernel at the time.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The study concluded that 40% of the issues could not occur at all in a formally verified microkernel, and only 4% of the issues would remain entirely unmitigated in such a system.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] More recent work on microkernels has been focusing on formal specifications of the kernel API, and formal proofs of the API's security properties and implementation correctness.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] The first example of this is a mathematical proof of the confinement mechanisms in EROS, based on a simplified model of the EROS API.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] More recently (in 2007) a comprehensive set of machine-checked proofs was performed of the properties of the protection model of seL4, a version of L4.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Examples are Coyotos, seL4, Nova, Redox and Fiasco.OC.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] In the case of seL4, complete formal verification of the implementation has been achieved, i.e. a mathematical proof that the kernel's implementation is consistent with its formal specification.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] This provides a guarantee that the properties proved about the API actually hold for the real kernel, a degree of assurance which goes beyond even CC EAL7.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] It was followed by proofs of security-enforcement properties of the API, and a proof demonstrating that the executable binary code is a correct translation of the C implementation, taking the compiler out of the TCB.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] Taken together, these proofs establish an end-to-end proof of security properties of the kernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/microkernel] There is also at least one case where the term nanokernel refers not to a small kernel, but one that supports a nanosecond clock resolution.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The product was originally developed in the early 1980s by Canadian company Quantum Software Systems, founded March 30, 1980, and later renamed QNX Software Systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] As of 2022, it is used in a variety of devices, including automobiles, medical devices, programmable logic controllers, automated manufacturing, trains.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Gordon Bell and Dan Dodge, both students at the University of Waterloo in 1980, took a course in real-time operating systems, in which the students constructed a basic real-time microkernel and user programs.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Both were convinced there was a commercial need for such a system, and moved to the high-tech planned community Kanata, Ontario, to start Quantum Software Systems that year.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] In 1982, the first version of QUNIX was released for the Intel 8088 CPU.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] In 1984, Quantum Software Systems renamed QUNIX to QNX (Quantum's Network eXecutive) in an effort to avoid any trademark infringement challenges.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] One of the first widespread uses of the QNX real-time OS (RTOS) was in the nonembedded world when it was selected as the operating system for the Ontario education system's own computer design, the Unisys ICON.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Over the years QNX was used mostly for larger projects, as its 44k kernel was too large to fit inside the one-chip computers of the era.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The system garnered a reputation for reliability and became used in running machinery in many industrial applications.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] In the late-1980s, Quantum realized that the market was rapidly moving towards the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) model and decided to rewrite the kernel to be much more compatible at a low level.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] During this time Patrick Hayden, while working as an intern, along with Robin Burgener (a full-time employee at the time), developed a new windowing system.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] This patented concept was developed into the embeddable graphical user interface (GUI) named the QNX Photon microGUI.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] QNX also provided a version of the X Window System.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] This resulted in QNX Neutrino, released in 2001.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Along with the Neutrino kernel, QNX Software Systems became a founding member of the Eclipse (integrated development environment) consortium.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The company released a suite of Eclipse plug-ins packaged with the Eclipse workbench in 2002, and named QNX Momentics Tool Suite.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] In 2004, the company announced it had been sold to Harman International Industries.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Before this acquisition, QNX software was already widely used in the automotive industry for telematics systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Since the purchase by Harman, QNX software has been designed into over 270 different automobile makes and models, in telematics systems, and in infotainment and navigation units.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The QNX CAR Application Platform was running in over 20 million vehicles as of mid-2011.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The company has since released several middleware products including the QNX Aviage Multimedia Suite, the QNX Aviage Acoustic Processing Suite and the QNX HMI Suite.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The microkernels of Cisco Systems' IOS-XR (ultra high availability IOS, introduced 2004) and IOS Software Modularity (introduced 2006) were based on QNX.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] IOS Software Modularity never gained traction and was limited only to small run for Catalyst 6500, while IOS XR moved to Linux as of release 6.0x.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] In September 2007, QNX Software Systems announced the availability of some of its source code.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] On April 9, 2010, Research In Motion (later renamed to BlackBerry Limited) announced they would acquire QNX Software Systems from Harman International Industries.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] On the same day, QNX source code access was restricted from the public and hobbyists.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] In September 2010, the company announced a tablet computer, the BlackBerry PlayBook, and a new operating system BlackBerry Tablet OS based on QNX to run on the tablet.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] On October 18, 2011, Research In Motion announced "BBX", which was later renamed *BlackBerry 10*, in December 2011.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Blackberry 10 devices build upon the BlackBerry PlayBook QNX based operating system for touch devices, but adapt the user interface for smartphones using the Qt based Cascades Native User-Interface framework.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] At the Geneva Motor Show, Apple demonstrated CarPlay which provides an iOS-like user interface to head units in compatible vehicles.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Once configured by the automaker, QNX can be programmed to hand off its display and some functions to an Apple CarPlay device.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] On December 11, 2014, Ford Motor Company stated that it would replace Microsoft Auto with QNX.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] In January 2017, QNX announced the upcoming release of its SDP 7.0, with support for Intel and ARM 32- and 64-bit platforms, and support for C++14.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] In December 2023, QNX released QNX SDP 8.0 which is powered by a next generation microkernel with support for the latest Intel and ARM [v8 and v9] 64 bit platforms, GCC12 based toolchain and a QNX toolkit for Visual Studio Code.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] As a microkernel-based OS, QNX is based on the idea of running most of the operating system kernel in the form of a number of small tasks, named Resource Managers.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] This differs from the more traditional monolithic kernel, in which the operating system kernel is one very large program composed of a huge number of parts, with special abilities.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] In the case of QNX, the use of a microkernel allows users (developers) to turn off any functions they do not need without having to change the OS.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Instead, such services will simply not run.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The QNX kernel, `procnto` (also name of the binary executable program for the QNX Neutrino ('nto') process ('proc') itself), contains only CPU scheduling, interprocess communication, interrupt redirection and timers.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Everything else runs as a user process, including a special process known as `proc` which performs process creation and memory management by operating in conjunction with the microkernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] This is made possible by two key mechanisms: subroutine-call type interprocess communication, and a boot loader which can load an image containing the kernel and any desired set of user programs and shared libraries.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] There are no device drivers in the kernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The network stack is based on NetBSD code.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Along with its support for its own, native, device drivers, QNX supports its legacy, *io-net manager* server, and the network drivers ported from NetBSD.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] QNX interprocess communication consists of sending a message from one process to another and waiting for a reply.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] This is a single operation, called `MsgSend`.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The message is copied, by the kernel, from the address space of the sending process to that of the receiving process.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] If the receiving process is waiting for the message, control of the CPU is transferred at the same time, without a pass through the CPU scheduler.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Thus, sending a message to another process and waiting for a reply does not result in "losing one's turn" for the CPU.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] This tight integration between message passing and CPU scheduling is one of the key mechanisms that makes QNX message passing broadly usable.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Most Unix and Linux interprocess communication mechanisms lack this tight integration, although a user space implementation of QNX-type messaging for Linux does exist.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Mishandling of this subtle issue is a primary reason for the disappointing performance of some other microkernel systems such as early versions of Mach.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The recipient process need not be on the same physical machine.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] All I/O operations, file system operations, and network operations were meant to work through this mechanism, and the data transferred was copied during message passing.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Later versions of QNX reduce the number of separate processes and integrate the network stack and other function blocks into single applications for performance reasons.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Message handling is prioritized by thread priority.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Since I/O requests are performed using message passing, high priority threads receive I/O service before low priority threads, an essential feature in a hard real-time system.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The boot loader is the other key component of the minimal microkernel system.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Because user programs can be built into the boot image, the set of device drivers and support libraries needed for startup need not be, and are not, in the kernel.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Even such functions as program loading are not in the kernel, but instead are in shared user-space libraries loaded as part of the boot image.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] It is possible to put an entire boot image into ROM, which is used for diskless embedded systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Neutrino supports symmetric multiprocessing and processor affinity, called bound multiprocessing (BMP) in QNX terminology.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] BMP is used to improve cache hitting and to ease the migration of non-SMP safe applications to multi-processor computers.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Neutrino supports strict priority-preemptive scheduling and adaptive partition scheduling (APS).
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] APS guarantees minimum CPU percentages to selected groups of threads, even though others may have higher priority.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The adaptive partition scheduler is still strictly priority-preemptive when the system is underloaded.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] It can also be configured to run a selected set of critical threads strictly real time, even when the system is overloaded.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The QNX operating system also contained a web browser known as 'Voyager'.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Due to its microkernel architecture QNX is also a distributed operating system.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Dan Dodge and Peter van der Veen hold U.S.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Patent 6,697,876: Distributed kernel operating system based on the QNX operating system's distributed processing features known commercially as Transparent Distributed Processing.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] This allows the QNX kernels on separate devices to access each other's system services using effectively the same communication mechanism as is used to access local services.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The Netpliance i-Opener uses a version of QNX as the primary operating system.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The BlackBerry PlayBook tablet computer designed by BlackBerry uses a version of QNX as the primary operating system.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] The BlackBerry 10 operating system is also based on QNX.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] QNX is also used in car infotainment systems with many major car makers offering variants that include an embedded QNX architecture.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] Since the introduction of its "Safe Kernel 1.0" in 2010, QNX was projected and used subsequently in automated drive or ADAS systems for automotive projects that require a functional safety certified RTOS.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] QNX provides this with its QNX OS for Safety products.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] QNX Neutrino (2001) has been ported to a number of platforms and now runs on practically any modern central processing unit (CPU) family that is used in the embedded market.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] This includes the PowerPC, x86, MIPS, SH-4, and the closely interrelated group of ARM, StrongARM, and XScale.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] As of 16 December 2025, QNX software is now embedded in over 275 million vehicles worldwide, including most leading OEMs and Tier 1s, such as BMW, Bosch, Continental, Dongfeng Motor, Geely, Ford, Honda, Mercedes-Benz, Subaru, Toyota, Volkswagen, Volvo, and more.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] On January 6, 2025, QNX made its software development platform available for non-commercial use.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] QNX offers a license for noncommercial and academic users.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] In January 2024, BlackBerry introduced QNX Everywhere to make QNX more accessible to Hobbyists.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] QNX Everywhere was made publicly accessible in early 2024.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] QNX Standard Support is available for a BSP that is listed below as available on QNX Software Center.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] For other BSPs, alternative forms of support (e.g., custom support plans, etc.) may be available or required from the “BSP Supplier” or “Board Vendor” indicated below.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] BlackBerry QNX has worked with a network of partner organizations to provide complementary technologies.
[src:qnx-rtos/qnx] These important relationships have ability to provide the foundational software, middleware, and services behind critical embedded systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A **real-time operating system** (**RTOS**) is an operating system (OS) for real-time computing applications that processes data and events that have critically defined time constraints.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS mainly targets resource constrained devices like microcontrollers.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] It is distinct from a time-sharing operating system, such as Unix, which manages the sharing of system resources with a scheduler, data buffers, or fixed task prioritization in multitasking or multiprogramming environments.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] All operations must verifiably complete within given time and resource constraints or else the RTOS will fail safe.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Real-time operating systems are event-driven and preemptive, meaning the OS can monitor the relevant priority of competing tasks, and make changes to the task priority.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A key characteristic of an RTOS is the level of its consistency concerning the amount of time it takes to accept and complete an application's task; the variability is "jitter".
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The chief design goal is not high throughput, but rather a guarantee of a soft or hard performance category.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS that can usually or generally meet a deadline is a soft real-time OS, but if it can meet a deadline deterministically it is a hard real-time OS.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS has an advanced algorithm for scheduling.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Scheduler flexibility enables a wider, computer-system orchestration of process priorities, but a real-time OS is more frequently dedicated to a narrow set of applications.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Key factors in a real-time OS are minimal interrupt latency and minimal thread switching latency; a real-time OS is valued more for how quickly or how predictably it can respond than for the amount of work it can perform in a given period of time.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Time sharing designs switch tasks more often than strictly needed, but give smoother multitasking, giving the illusion that a process or user has sole use of a machine.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Early CPU designs needed many cycles to switch tasks during which the CPU could do nothing else useful.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Because switching took so long, early OSes tried to minimize wasting CPU time by avoiding unnecessary task switching.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Blocked (waiting for an event, I/O for example).
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Most tasks are blocked or ready most of the time because generally only one task can run at a time per CPU core.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The number of items in the ready queue can vary greatly, depending on the number of tasks the system needs to perform and the type of scheduler that the system uses.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] On simpler non-preemptive but still multitasking systems, a task has to give up its time on the CPU to other tasks, which can cause the ready queue to have a greater number of overall tasks in the ready to be executed state (resource starvation).
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] If there are never more than a few tasks on the ready list, then a doubly linked list of ready tasks is likely optimal.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] If the ready list usually contains only a few tasks but occasionally contains more, then the list should be sorted by priority, so that finding the highest priority task to run does not require traversing the list.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Instead, inserting a task requires walking the list.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] During this search, preemption should not be inhibited.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Long critical sections should be divided into smaller pieces.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] If an interrupt occurs that makes a high priority task ready during the insertion of a low priority task, that high priority task can be inserted and run immediately before the low priority task is inserted.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The critical response time, sometimes called the flyback time, is the time it takes to queue a new ready task and restore the state of the highest priority task to running.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In a well-designed RTOS, readying a new task will take 3 to 20 instructions per ready-queue entry, and restoration of the highest-priority ready task will take 5 to 30 instructions.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In advanced systems, real-time tasks share computing resources with many non-real-time tasks, and the ready list can be arbitrarily long.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In such systems, a scheduler ready list implemented as a linked list would be inadequate.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A multitasking operating system like Unix is poor at real-time tasks.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The scheduler gives the highest priority to jobs with the lowest demand on the computer, so there is no way to ensure that a time-critical job will have access to enough resources.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Multitasking systems must manage sharing data and hardware resources among multiple tasks.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] It is usually unsafe for two tasks to access the same specific data or hardware resource simultaneously.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] General-purpose operating systems usually do not allow user programs to mask (disable) interrupts, because the user program could control the CPU for as long as it is made to.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Some modern CPUs do not allow user mode code to disable interrupts as such control is considered a key operating system resource.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Many embedded systems and RTOSs, however, allow the application itself to run in kernel mode for greater system call efficiency and also to permit the application to have greater control of the operating environment without requiring OS intervention.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] On single-processor systems, an application running in kernel mode and masking interrupts is the lowest overhead method to prevent simultaneous access to a shared resource.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] While interrupts are masked and the current task does not make a blocking OS call, the current task has *exclusive* use of the CPU since no other task or interrupt can take control, so the critical section is protected.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When the task exits its critical section, it must unmask interrupts; pending interrupts, if any, will then execute.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Temporarily masking interrupts should only be done when the longest path through the critical section is shorter than the desired maximum interrupt latency.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Typically this method of protection is used only when the critical section is just a few instructions and contains no loops.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This method is ideal for protecting hardware bit-mapped registers when the bits are controlled by different tasks.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When the shared resource must be reserved without blocking all other tasks (such as waiting for Flash memory to be written), it is better to use mechanisms also available on general-purpose operating systems, such as a mutex and OS-supervised interprocess messaging.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Such mechanisms involve system calls, and usually invoke the OS's dispatcher code on exit, so they typically take hundreds of CPU instructions to execute, while masking interrupts may take as few as one instruction on some processors.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A (non-recursive) mutex is either **locked** or unlocked.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When a task has locked the mutex, all other tasks must wait for the mutex to be unlocked by its *owner* - the original thread.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A task may set a timeout on its wait for a mutex.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] There are several well-known problems with mutex based designs such as priority inversion and deadlocks.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In priority inversion a high priority task waits because a low priority task has a mutex, but the lower priority task is not given CPU time to finish its work.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A typical solution is to have the task that owns a mutex 'inherit' the priority of the highest waiting task.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] But this simple approach gets more complex when there are multiple levels of waiting: task *A* waits for a mutex locked by task *B*, which waits for a mutex locked by task *C*.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Handling multiple levels of inheritance causes other code to run in high priority context and thus can cause starvation of medium-priority threads.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In a deadlock, two or more tasks lock mutex without timeouts and then wait forever for the other task's mutex, creating a cyclic dependency.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The simplest deadlock scenario occurs when two tasks alternately lock two mutex, but in the opposite order.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Deadlock is prevented by careful design.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The other approach to resource sharing is for tasks to send messages in an organized message passing scheme.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In this paradigm, the resource is managed directly by only one task.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When another task wants to interrogate or manipulate the resource, it sends a message to the managing task.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Although their real-time behavior is less crisp than semaphore systems, simple message-based systems avoid most protocol deadlock hazards, and are generally better-behaved than semaphore systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] However, problems like those of semaphores are possible.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Priority inversion can occur when a task is working on a low-priority message and ignores a higher-priority message (or a message originating indirectly from a high priority task) in its incoming message queue.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Protocol deadlocks can occur when two or more tasks wait for each other to send response messages.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Since an interrupt handler blocks the highest priority task from running, and since real-time operating systems are designed to keep thread latency to a minimum, interrupt handlers are typically kept as short as possible.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The interrupt handler defers all interaction with the hardware if possible; typically all that is necessary is to acknowledge or disable the interrupt (so that it won't occur again when the interrupt handler returns) and notify a task that work needs to be done.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This can be done by unblocking a driver task through releasing a semaphore, setting a flag or sending a message.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A scheduler often provides the ability to unblock a task from interrupt handler context.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An OS maintains catalogues of objects it manages such as threads, mutexes, memory, and so on.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Updates to this catalogue must be strictly controlled.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, it can be problematic when an interrupt handler calls an OS function while the application is in the act of also doing so.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The OS function called from an interrupt handler could find the object database to be in an inconsistent state because of the application's update.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] There are two major approaches to deal with this problem: the unified architecture and the segmented architecture.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] RTOSs implementing the unified architecture solve the problem by simply disabling interrupts while the internal catalogue is updated.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The downside of this is that interrupt latency increases, potentially losing interrupts.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The segmented architecture does not make direct OS calls but delegates the OS related work to a separate handler.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This handler runs at a higher priority than any thread but lower than the interrupt handlers.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The advantage of this architecture is that it adds very few cycles to interrupt latency.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] As a result, OSes which implement the segmented architecture are more predictable and can deal with higher interrupt rates compared to the unified architecture.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Similarly, the System Management Mode on x86 compatible hardware can take a lot of time before it returns control to the operating system.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Memory allocation is more critical in a real-time operating system than in other operating systems.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] First, for stability there cannot be memory leaks (memory that is allocated but not freed after use).
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The device should work indefinitely, without ever needing a reboot.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, dynamic memory allocation is frowned upon.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Whenever possible, all required memory allocation is specified statically at compile time.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Another reason to avoid dynamic memory allocation is memory fragmentation.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] With frequent allocation and releasing of small chunks of memory, a situation may occur where available memory is divided into several sections and the RTOS cannot allocate a large enough continuous block of memory, although there is enough free memory.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Secondly, speed of allocation is important.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A standard memory allocation scheme scans a linked list of indeterminate length to find a suitable free memory block, which is unacceptable in a RTOS since memory allocation has to occur within a certain amount of time.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Because mechanical disks have much longer and more unpredictable response times, swapping to disk files is not used for the same reasons as RAM allocation discussed above.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The simple fixed-size-blocks algorithm works quite well for simple embedded systems because of its low overhead.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] While all RTOSes are able to run on microcontrollers they have ports for, some RTOSes like Zephyr are capable of abstracting even further a number of device drivers like External Flash, I2C devices or internal peripherals like UART commands and sleep modes.
[src:qnx-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This helps offload the need for a developer to create drivers and instead a set of APIs are given for unsupported drivers to be ported over while supported ones are ready for use within the application code.
